he property)."]}]},{"name":"Brome","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English, Scottish:  see  Broom  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Broom","meanings":["English: variant of   Broome  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":39,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Brome I was born in 1220, in Norfolk, England, his father, Henry de Brome, was 20 and his mother, Alice de Newburgh, was 21. He married Mrs. William de Brome in 1239, in Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1267, in his hometown, at the age of 47."},"et":{